\pard\sl240\slmult1\qc\fs24\lang9 THE MASTER LIST OF UNIVERSAL PRINCIPLES\par
First Principles for High-Dimensional Projection\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
This document represents a complete architectural framework of human knowledge \par
regarding how systems move and resolve. It serves as the foundational "code" \par
for projecting the Path of Least Action within a 4D tesseract manifold.\par
\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
I. OPTIMIZATION AND TRAJECTORY\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\par
1. The Principle of Least Action (Hamilton's Principle)\par
   Nature always chooses a path where the Action\f1\emdash the integral of the difference \par
   between kinetic and potential energy\emdash is stationary. In this model, the "path" \par
   between draws is the one that minimizes the "tension" in the tesseract.\par
\par
2. Fermat\rquote s Principle (Principle of Least Time)\par
   The path taken by a ray of light between two points is the path that can be \par
   traversed in the least time. If the "Eye" is the sender of information, the \par
   "refractive index" of the system determines where the beam "lands" on the \par
   retina of the next draw.\par
\par
3. The Maupertuis Principle\par
   A precursor to Least Action that focuses on the shape of the path rather \par
   than timing. It states that a particle follows the path that minimizes the \par
   product of its momentum and the distance traveled.\par
\par
4. The Ergodic Principle\par
   In a stable system, the average of a process over time is the same as the \par
   average over all possible states at one time. This tells you that \par
   eventually, the "Path of Least Action" will touch every vertex of the \par
   tesseract.\par
\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
II. SYMMETRY, STABILITY, AND CONSERVATION\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\par
5. Noether\rquote s Theorem\par
   Connects Symmetries to Conservation Laws. If a system remains unchanged \par
   under rotation or time-shifts, a quantity like momentum or energy is \par
   conserved.\par
\par
6. The Curie Symmetry Principle\par
   A physical effect cannot have a spatial asymmetry that is not already \par
   present in its causes. If the "result" is skewed, the "cause" must be skewed.\par
\par
7. The Principle of Relativity\par
   The laws of physics are the same in all inertial frames of reference. The \par
   4D model should work whether the "Eye" is at the center of the tesseract \par
   or at one of the vertices.\par
\par
8. Le Chatelier's Principle\par
   If a system at equilibrium is disturbed, the system will shift in a way \par
   that counteracts the disturbance. If a draw "disturbs" the statistical \par
   equilibrium, the next draws will "shift" to restore balance.\par
\par
9. The Equipartition Theorem\par
   In thermal equilibrium, energy is shared equally among all of its various \par
   forms. The universe wants to spread energy out rather than letting it pool.\par
\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
III. THERMODYNAMICS AND INFORMATION THEORY\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\par
10. The Principle of Maximum Entropy (Jaynes' Principle)\par
    The probability distribution that best represents the current state of \par
    knowledge is the one with the largest entropy. Unless forced by info, \par
    a system seeks the state of maximum "spread" or disorder.\par
\par
11. The Second Law of Thermodynamics (Entropy Arrow)\par
    Entropy in an isolated system always increases. This creates an "Arrow \par
    of Information" where projections are more accurate for the next draw \par
    than for several weeks away.\par
\par
12. The Holographic Principle\par
    The description of a volume of space can be encoded on a lower-dimensional \par
    boundary. This justifies projecting the 4D "volume" of the tesseract \par
    onto the 2D "surface" of a screen.\par
\par
13. Landauer\rquote s Principle\par
    Any logically irreversible manipulation of information must be accompanied \par
    by a corresponding increase in entropy. Information is physical.\par
\par
14. The Principle of Stationary Phase (The Quantum Path)\par
    While a particle technically takes every possible path, the paths that are \par
    not near the "Path of Least Action" interfere and cancel out. Only the \par
    "stationary" path survives to become reality.\par
\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
IV. SYSTEMIC CONSTRAINTS AND MECHANICS\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\par
15. The Pauli Exclusion Principle\par
    Two fermions cannot occupy the same quantum state. In a lottery, this is \par
    the hard constraint where two balls cannot occupy the same "slot".\par
\par
16. The Principle of Superposition\par
    A system exists in all theoretically possible states simultaneously until \par
    it is observed. The "Eye" (the observer) collapses this wave into a \par
    single, physical reality.\par
\par
17. The Principle of Locality & Non-Locality (Bell\rquote s Theorem)\par
    Locality says objects are only influenced by surroundings, while \par
    Non-locality proves particles can be connected regardless of distance.\par
\par
18. The Principle of Boundedness (The Extremum Principle)\par
    Every physical system has a limit\emdash a maximum or minimum boundary. These \par
    walls act as a "containment field" that forces the path to fold back on \par
    itself.\par
\par
19. Mach\rquote s Principle\par
    The local motion of a particle is determined by the large-scale \par
    distribution of all matter in the universe. "Local" is a subset of "Global".\par
\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
V. LOGIC AND META-PHYSICS\par
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\par
20. The Principle of Parsimony (Occam\rquote s Razor)\par
    The simplest solution with the fewest assumptions is the most likely. \par
    Complexity is expensive.\par
\par
21. The Principle of Universality\par
    In complex systems, many different components can lead to the same \par
    aggregate behavior near a "critical point".\par
\par
22. The Principle of Reciprocity\par
    In systems out of equilibrium, there is a symmetrical relationship \par
    between different types of "flows" and "forces".\par
\par
23. The Principle of Self-Organization (Synergetics)\par
    In open systems, patterns can emerge spontaneously from "noise" when a \par
    certain threshold of information is reached.\par
\par
24. The Anthropic Principle\par
    The system exists as a coherent path specifically because an observer \par
    is looking for it.\par
\par
25. The Principle of Non-Contradiction\par
    A thing cannot be both "A" and "not-A" at the same time and in the same \par
    sense. This is the baseline for Integer vs. Null logic.\par
\par
26. The Principle of Causal Determinism\par
    Every event is necessitated by antecedent circumstances and conditions \par
    together with the laws of nature.\par
\par
27. The Principle of Complementarity (Bohr\rquote s Principle)\par
    Objects have complementary properties (like wave-particle duality) that \par
    cannot be measured simultaneously.\par
\par
28. The Incompleteness Principle (G\f0\'f6del)\par
    In any sufficiently powerful logical system, there are true statements \par
    that cannot be proven within that system. There will always be a \par
    "residual" or "null" factor\f1\emdash the wildcard of the universe.\par

